I will not fill the missing values in the users' score column. I think that the same game can be rated very differently on different platforms, so I think that it is not correct to take the user score of the game from the other platform.

The majority of "tbd" refer to the far gone years and it doesn't seem that anyone will go backwards and determine it. 1099 values for the user rank were taken from the games from other platforms.

The H0 hypothesis: the average user rating of the Xbox One is the same as user rating of the PC platform. The H1 hypothesis: the average user ratings of the Xbox One and of the PC platform are different.

I will treat the variances of the samples as equal.

sample_2 = data_PC['user_score']

alpha = 0.05
                        
results = st.ttest_ind(
        sample_1, 
        sample_2)

print('p-value: ', results.pvalue)

if (results.pvalue < alpha):
    print("We reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value:  0.2846882962681825
We can't reject the null hypothesis

Step 6. Write a general conclusion¶

General conclusion:¶

For the research I've got a data set of 16715 entries. As the info was gathered from the open sources - it had pretty many missing values and even some mistakes. I have preprocessed the data and started the research. I have investigated how different parameters influence the sales of the games on different platforms.

The data set had the info on the games starting back to 1980-ies. Of course the info scope on the more recent games was bigger and more relevant for the research. The first growth sprut in the number of the released games can be observed in 1994. Then the number of the released games was increasing each year till 2008. Then the number of the games started to drop each year. In 2016 the number of released games was similar to 2001.

The avarage lifecycle of the gaming platform is about 10 years. It takes few years for the platform to arrive to its peak in sales and then sales start to decrease till the platform gets to zero. The researched platforms from the year 2000 to 2016 are or dead or shrinking significantly. For the majority of the platforms the better part of the values of the sales lies below the mean (Wii and PS2 are the exceptions), meaning that the sales were decreasing from year to year. So, the bigest sales had: PS2, X360, PS3, Wii, DS, and PS platforms. On the example of X360 platform I have studied the influence of the users' and professional reviews on the sales of the games and got to the conclusion that the majority of the well sold games had high professional and user rating. I took the list of the games released on X360 and checked them on other platforms and saw the same pattern - high scores - high sales.

I have studied the genres of the games as well and noticed that 'Action' games are the most popular, but still the breakaway is not that big. The most profitable genres are "active" gaming and less profitable are the "intelectual". As the table contained the info on sales in different regions, I studied the peculiarities of North American, European and Japanese markets. North American market share of the games is similar to the European, Japanese market differs a bit more from NA and EU. In terms of the genres popularity: 'Action' and 'Sports' are commonly popular in all regions, but 'Racing' is popular in EU only, as 'Role-playing' genre is specific for Japan only. In terms of ESRB raiting all the three regions that we are researching have the same four categories of the games - "E", "T", "M" and "E10+" in a bit different proportions. Other rated games have very few sales.

Our statistical tests have shown that XB One and PC platforms are rated differently by the users as well as action and sports games are rated differently by the users. As we remember from the previous research on the users' rating - it is an important factor for the sales.

As for the year 2017 I would recommend to focus on the local markets and provide them with the games of popular genres and platforms specifically for the regions. If the new version of the platforms will be released for NA region I would recommend to count on XBox and Sony Play Station, for the EU region - on Sony Play Station and for Japan - on Nintendo. In the past 5 years PS4 and 3DS were the only platforms with positive growing in sales.
